The `alias` example applies `@Modifier.rename` / `@Modifier.alias` to a standalone case class (`MyClass`). `rename`/`alias` are `Modifier.Term`s and are only interpreted for record fields or variant cases (e.g., sealed-trait cases) by codecs like `JsonBinaryCodecDeriver`; on a plain product type this annotation won’t affect encoding/decoding. Consider moving these annotations onto a specific field, or change the example to a sum type where `MyClass` is a case that extends a sealed trait so the case name aliasing is actually exercised.
```suggestion
sealed trait MyType

object MyType {
  @Modifier.rename("NewName")
  @Modifier.alias("OldName")
  @Modifier.alias("LegacyName")
  case class RenamedCase(value: String) extends MyType

  implicit val schema: Schema[MyType] = Schema.derived
```

This branch applies the alias's `id.typeArgs` onto the underlying `TypeId` via `normalizeWithArgs`, which can change the meaning of aliases that expand to a non-type-constructor `Ref`. For example, `type Const[A] = Foo` when used as `Const[Int]` would incorrectly normalize toward something resembling `Foo[Int]` (i.e., it attaches args to `Foo`) instead of normalizing to just `Foo`. Similarly, `type Alias[A] = A` should normalize to the actual argument, not a type-param `TypeId` decorated with args. Suggestion: instead of pushing `id.typeArgs` into `underlying`, perform parameter substitution on the aliased-to representation (e.g., build a `paramToArg` map from `id.typeParams`/`id.typeArgs` and call `substituteTypeRepr` on `TypeRepr.Ref(underlying)`), then normalize the substituted `TypeRepr`. If the underlying `Ref` does not reference alias parameters, normalization should ignore the alias args rather than attach them.
```suggestion
          val baseRepr = TypeRepr.Ref(underlying)
          val substitutedRepr =
            if (id.typeParams.nonEmpty && id.typeArgs.nonEmpty) {
