`Resource.map` always returns `Resource.Unique`, which drops sharing/memoization semantics when mapping over a shared resource. If a `Resource.Shared[A]` is mapped, repeated `make` calls in the same scope will re-run `f` (and may allocate new `B` values) even though the underlying `A` is memoized, which is surprising and can break expected sharing of derived resources. Consider preserving the original resource's sharing mode (e.g., map to `Resource.shared` when `self` is shared, otherwise `Resource.unique`) so the mapped value is memoized consistently with the source resource.
```suggestion
  def map[B](f: A => B): Resource[B] =
    new Resource[B] {
      private[this] val cache = new AtomicReference[(Finalizer, B)]()

      private[scope] def make(finalizer: Finalizer): B = {
        val current = cache.get()
        if (current != null && (current._1 eq finalizer)) current._2
        else {
          val value = f(self.make(finalizer))
          cache.set((finalizer, value))
          value
        }
      }
    }
```

`normalizeTypeRepr` can construct “nested applied” shapes (e.g. `Applied(Applied(...), args)`) or leave un-substituted alias parameters when a type alias is used as the *tycon* of an `Applied` node (i.e. `TypeRepr.Applied(TypeRepr.Ref(aliasId), args)`). This happens because alias expansion is only handled for `TypeRepr.Ref(id)` and the alias branch uses `TypeRepr.Ref(normalize(underlying))` which can still be `isApplied`, which then gets rewritten later into `Applied(Ref(unapplied), ...)` and can become nested under the outer `Applied`.
```suggestion
          val resolvedArgs     = resolveTypeArgs(id.typeParams, id.typeArgs, aliasArgs)
          val normUnderlying   = normalize(underlying)
          val normResolvedArgs = resolvedArgs.map(normalizeTypeRepr)
          if (normUnderlying.isApplied) {
            val allArgs =
              normUnderlying.typeArgs.map(normalizeTypeRepr) ++ normResolvedArgs
            TypeRepr.Applied(TypeRepr.Ref(unapplied(normUnderlying)), allArgs)
          } else {
            TypeRepr.Applied(TypeRepr.Ref(normUnderlying), normResolvedArgs)
          }
